Root User 
1. Created automatically when an AWS acccount is created.
2. Full, unrestricted access to all AWS services and account-level settings.
3. Very powerful and not used for daily tasks.
4. Used only for account-level tasks (billing, account closure, MFA).
5. MFA must be enabled.

# Root-only actions: (This cannot be done by IAM users even with AdministratorAccess)
1. Change account email
2. Change root password
3. Enable / disable root MFA
4. Close AWS account
5. Change support plan
6. View billing & payment info (by default)
7. Register for some services initially

IAM user
1. Identities created inside the AWS account for specific people or applications.
2. Given only required permissions using IAM policies, following the principle of least privilege.
3. Used for day-to-day operations.
4. Starts with no permissions by default.

# IAM users are used for:
1. Creating resources (EC2, S3, RDS, etc.)
2. Managing IAM policies & roles (if allowed)
3. Running CLI / SDK
4. Daily operational work